'''Folic acid''' (also known as '''folate''', '''vitamin M''', '''vitamin B<sub>9</sub>''',<ref>{{cite web | last = Ural | first = Serdar H. | title = Folic Acid and Pregnancy. | publisher = Kid's Health | date = 2008-11 | url = http://kidshealth.org/parent/pregnancy_newborn/pregnancy/folic_acid.html }}</ref> '''vitamin B<sub>c</sub>'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/vitamin+Bc |title=Definition of vitamin Bc|publisher=Medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> (or '''folacin'''), '''pteroyl-[[glutamic acid|L-glutamic acid]]''', '''pteroyl-[[glutamate|L-glutamate]]''', and '''pteroylmonoglutamic acid<ref name="mayofolate">Mayo Clinic Web Editors . Folate. http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/folate/NS_patient-folate/DSECTION=synonyms (accessed Nov 15, 2010),additional text.</ref>''') are [[chemical formula|form]]s of the [[water-soluble]] [[B vitamins|vitamin B<sub>9</sub>]]. Folate is composed of the aromatic pteridine ring linked to para-aminobenzoic acid and one or more glutamate residues. Folic acid is itself not biologically active, but its biological importance is due to [[tetrahydrofolate]] and other derivatives after its conversion to [[dihydrofolic acid]] in the [[liver]].<ref name="Bailey">{{cite journal |author=Bailey SW, Ayling JE  |title=The extremely slow and variable activity of dihydrofolate reductase in human liver and its implications for high folic acid intake |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=106 |issue=36 |pages=15424–9  |year=2009 |month=September |pmid=19706381 |pmc=2730961 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0902072106}}</ref>

Vitamin B<sub>9</sub> (folic acid and folate) is [[essential nutrient|essential]] for numerous [[physiology|bodily function]]s. Humans cannot synthesize folate de novo; therefore, folate has to be supplied through the diet to meet their daily requirements. The human body needs folate to synthesize DNA, repair DNA, and methylate DNA as well as to act as a cofactor in certain biological reactions.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite journal | last1 = Weinstein | first1 = SJ ''et al.'' | year = 2003 | title = Null Association Between Prostate Cancer and Serum Folate, Vitamin B6, Vitamin B12, and Homocysteine | url =http://cebp.aacrjournals.org/content/12/11/1271.full.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=1 December 2010 | journal = Cancer Epidemiology, Biomarkers, & Prevention | volume = 12 | issue = 11| pages = 1271–1272 }}</ref> It is especially important in aiding rapid [[cell division]] and [[cell growth|growth]], such as in infancy and pregnancy. [[Child]]ren and [[adult]]s both require folic acid to [[produce]] healthy [[red blood cell]]s and prevent [[anemia]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Dietary Supplement Fact Sheet: Folate. | publisher = Office of Dietary Supplements, National Institutes of Health | url = http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/folate.asp }}</ref>

Folate and folic acid derive their names from the [[Latin]] word ''[[Wiktionary:folium|folium]]'' (which means "leaf").  Leafy vegetables are principal sources of folic acid, although in Western diets fortified cereals and bread may be a larger dietary source.{{citation needed|date=October 2011}}

A lack of [[diet (nutrition)|dietary]] folates leads to [[folate deficiency]], which is uncommon in normal Western diets.{{citation needed|date=October 2011}}
A complete lack of dietary folate takes months before deficiency develops as normal individuals have about 500–20,000&nbsp;µg<ref>Gentili et al, 2009, Folic Acid Deficiency  http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/200184-overview</ref> of folate in body stores.<ref>National Health Service U.K., "Anaemia, vitamin B12 or folate deficiency – Causes" http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Anaemia-vitamin-B12-and-folate-deficiency/Pages/Causes.aspx</ref> This deficiency can result in many health problems, the most notable one being [[neural tube defects]] in developing embryos. Common symptoms of folate deficiency include diarrhea, [[macrocytic anemia]] with weakness or shortness of breath, nerve damage with weakness and limb numbness ([[peripheral neuropathy]]),<ref>Botez, M.I.1976. Folate deficiency and neurological disorders in adults. Medical Hypothesis.volume 2, issue 4 pages 135–140</ref> pregnancy complications, mental confusion, forgetfulness or other cognitive declines, mental depression, sore or swollen tongue, peptic or mouth ulcers, headaches, heart palpitations, irritability, and behavioral disorders.  Low levels of folate can also lead to homocysteine accumulation.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> DNA synthesis and repair are impaired and this could lead to cancer development.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

==Health benefits and risks==

===Pregnancy===

Adequate folate intake during the [[preconception period]] (which is the time right before and just after a woman becomes pregnant) helps protect against a number of [[Congenital disorder|congenital malformations]], including [[neural tube defect]]s (which are the most notable birth defects that occur from folate deficiency).<ref name="Oldref_21">{{cite journal|author=Shaw GM, Schaffer D, Velie EM, Morland K, Harris JA |title=Periconceptional vitamin use, dietary folate, and the occurrence of neural tube defects|journal=Epidemiology|volume=6|issue=3|year=1995|pages=219–226|pmid=7619926|doi=10.1097/00001648-199505000-00005}}</ref>  Neural tube defects are severe abnormalities of the central nervous system that develop in babies during the first few weeks of pregnancy resulting in malformations of the spine, skull, and brain; the most common neural tube defects are  spina bifida and anencephaly. The risk of neural tube defects is significantly reduced when supplemental folic acid is consumed in addition to a healthy diet before conception and during the first month after conception.<ref name="Oldref_22">{{cite journal|author=Mulinare J, Cordero JF, Erickson JD, Berry RJ |title=Periconceptional use of multivitamins and the occurrence of neural tube defects|journal=Journal of the American Medical Association|volume=260|issue=21 |year=1988|pages=3141–3145|pmid=3184392|doi = 10.1001/jama.260.21.3141}}</ref><ref name="Oldref_23">{{cite journal|author=Milunsky A, Jick H, Jick SS, Bruell CL, MacLaughlin DS, Rothman KJ, Willett W |title=Multivitamin/folic acid supplementation in early pregnancy reduces the prevalence of neural tube defects|journal=Journal of the American Medical Association|volume=262|issue=20|year=1989|pages=2847–2852|pmid=2478730|doi=10.1001/jama.262.20.2847 |url=http://www.sjsu.edu/faculty/gerstman/eks/Milunsky1989.pdf}}</ref> Supplementation with folic acid has also been shown to reduce the risk of [[congenital heart defect]]s, [[Cleft lip and palate|cleft lip]]s,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wilcox | first1 = AJ | last2 = Lie | first2 = RT | last3 = Solvoll | first3 = K | last4 = Taylor | first4 = J |last5 = McConnaughey | first5 = DR | last6 = Abyholm | first6 = F | last7 = Vindenes | first7 = H | last8 = Vollset | first8 = SE | last9 = Drevon |first9 = CA | title = Folic acid supplements and risk of facial clefts: national population based case-control study | journal = BMJ (Clinical research ed.) | volume = 334 | issue = 7591 | page = 464 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17259187 | pmc = 1808175 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.39079.618287.0B }}</ref> limb defects, and urinary tract anomalies.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1080/01443610701814195 | last1 = Goh | first1 = YI | last2 = Koren | first2 = G | year = 2008 | title = Folic acid in pregnancy and fetal outcomes | url = | journal = J. Obstet. Gynaecol | volume = 28 | issue = 1| pages = 3–13 |pmid = 18259891 }}</ref>  Folate deficiency during pregnancy may also increase the risk of preterm delivery, infant low birth weight and fetal growth retardation, as well as increasing homocysteine level in the blood, which may lead to spontaneous abortion and pregnancy complications, such as [[placental abruption]] and [[pre-eclampsia]].<ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite journal |last1=Scholl |pmid=10799405 |first1=TO |last2=Johnson |first2=WG|title=Folic acid: influence on the outcome of pregnancy |journal=The American journal of clinical nutrition |volume=71 |issue=5 Suppl |pages= 1295S–1303S |year= 2000 }}</ref>  Women who could become pregnant are advised to eat foods fortified with folic acid or take supplements in addition to eating folate-rich foods to reduce the risk of serious birth defects.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wilton | first1 = DC | last2 = Foureur | first2 = MJ| title = A survey of folic acid use in primigravid women | journal = Women and birth : journal of the Australian College of Midwives | volume = 23 |issue = 2 | pages = 67–73 | year = 2010 | pmid = 19828392 | doi = 10.1016/j.wombi.2009.09.001 }}</ref> Taking 400 micrograms of synthetic folic acid daily from fortified foods and/or supplements has been suggested for all non-pregnant women, in order to have adequate folic acid intake even in case of unplanned pregnancies.<ref name=CDC>[http://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/folicacid/recommendations.html Health Professionals Recommendations, Folic Acid, NCBDDD, CDC]</ref> The RDA for folate equivalents for pregnant women is set at 600 micrograms,<ref>United States Department of Agriculture (USDA). 2010. Dietary Guidelines for Americans. 7th ed. Government Printing Office , Washington, DC, U.S.</ref> although a range of 400 micrograms up to 4 milligrams (4000 micrograms) reported in an old U.S.&nbsp;Public Health Service guideline is still followed by many health care providers, .<ref name=CDC/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00019479.htm|title=Recommendations for the Use of Folic Acid to Reduce the Number of Cases of Spina Bifida and Other Neural Tube Defects|date=11 September 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00014915.htm|title=Effectiveness in Disease and Injury Prevention Use of Folic Acid for Prevention of Spina Bifida and Other Neural Tube Defects -- 1983-1991|date=2 August 1991}}</ref><ref name="FAOWHO2002">{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/004/Y2809E/y2809e0a.htm|author1=[[FAO]]|author2=[[WHO]]|chapter=4 Folate and Folic Acid|title=Human Vitamin and Mineral Requirements|year=2002}}</ref>
The mechanisms and reasons why folic acid prevents birth defects is unknown.<ref name="Steegers-Theunissen">{{cite journal | last1 = Steegers-Theunissen | first1 = RP | last2 = Obermann-Borst | first2 = SA | last3 = Kremer | first3 = D | last4 = Lindemans | first4 = J | last5 = Siebel | first5 = C | last6 = Steegers | first6 = EA | last7 = Slagboom | first7 = PE |last8 = Heijmans | first8 = BT | last9 = Zhang | first9 = Cuilin | title = Periconceptional Maternal Folic Acid Use of 400 µg per Day Is Related to Increased Methylation of the IGF2 Gene in the Very Young Child | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 4 | issue = 11 | pages = e7845 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19924280 | pmc = 2773848 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0007845 | editor1-last = Zhang | editor1-first = Cuilin }}</ref> It is hypothesized that the insulin-like growth factor 2 gene is differentially methylated and these changes in IGF2 result in improved intrauterine growth and development.<ref name="Steegers-Theunissen"/>  Approximately 85% of women in an urban Irish study reported using folic acid supplements before they become pregnant, but only 18% used enough folic acid supplements to meet the current folic acid requirements due, it is reported, to socio-economic challenges.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = McGuire | first1 = M | last2 = Cleary | first2 = B | last3 = Sahm | first3 = L | last4 = Murphy | first4 = DJ | title = Prevalence and predictors of periconceptional folic acid uptake—prospective cohort study in an Irish urban obstetric population | journal = Human reproduction (Oxford, England) | volume = 25 | issue = 2 |pages = 535–43 | year = 2010 | pmid = 19910320 | doi = 10.1093/humrep/dep398 }}</ref>  Folic acid supplements may also protect the fetus against disease when the mother is battling a disease or taking medications or [[smoking and pregnancy|smoking during pregnancy]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Jia | first1 = ZL | last2 = Li | first2 = Y | last3 = Chen | first3 = CH | last4 = Li | first4 = S | last5 = Wang | first5 = Y | last6 = Zheng | first6 = Q | last7 = Shi | first7 = B | title = Association among polymorphisms at MYH9, environmental factors, and nonsyndromic orofacial clefts in western China | journal = DNA and cell biology | volume = 29 | issue = 1 | pages = 25–32 | year = 2010 | pmid = 19891592 | doi = 10.1089/dna.2009.0935}}</ref>

It also contributes to [[oocyte maturation]], [[Implantation (human embryo)|implantation]], [[placentation]], in addition to the general effects of [[#Human reproduction|folic acid and pregnancy]].  Therefore, it is necessary  to receive sufficient amounts through the diet to avoid [[subfertility]].<ref name="Ebisch IM, Thomas CM, Peters WH, Braat DD, Steegers-Theunissen RP 2007 163–74">{{cite journal |author=Ebisch IM, Thomas CM, Peters WH, Braat DD, Steegers-Theunissen RP  |title=The importance of folate, zinc and antioxidants in the pathogenesis and prevention of subfertility |journal=Hum Reprod Update |volume=13 |issue=2 |pages=163–74  |year=2007|pmid=17099205 |doi=10.1093/humupd/dml054 }}</ref>

There is growing concern worldwide that prenatal high folic acid in the presence of low vitamin B12 causes epigenetic changes in the unborn predisposing them to metabolic syndromes, central adiposity and adult diseases such as Type 2 diabetes.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?db=pubmed&cmd=Search&doptcmdl=Citation&defaultField=Title%20Word&term=Yajnik%5Bauthor%5D%20AND%20Maternal%20nutrition%2C%20intrauterine%20programming%20and%20consequential%20risks%20in%20the%20offspring |title=Maternal nutrition, intrauterine pro... [Rev Endocr Metab Disord. 2008&#93; - PubMed - NCBI |publisher=Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov |date=2012-05-24 |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref>  Another active area of research and concern is that either too much or too little folic acid in utero causes epigenetic changes to the brain leading to [[autism spectrum disorder]]s.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21454018 |title=Is excess folic acid supplementation a risk f... [Med Hypotheses. 2011&#93; - PubMed - NCBI |publisher=Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov |date=2012-05-24 |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/health/2013/02/25/171828067/folic-acid-for-pregnant-mothers-cuts-kids-autism-risk|accessdate=2013-03-08|date=|title=Folic Acid For Pregnant Mothers Cuts Kids' Autism Risk|agency=NPR|author=Jon Hamilton}}</ref><ref>http://www.kidsdr.com/your-baby/does-folic-acid-help-prevent-autism</ref>

===Sperm quality===

Folic acid may also reduce chromosomal defects in sperm.<ref name=Youngetal>{{cite journal |last1=Young|url=http://www.medpagetoday.com/upload/2008/3/21/den036v1.pdf |journal=Human reproduction (Oxford, England) |first1=SS |last2=Eskenazi |first2=B|last3=Marchetti |first3=FM |last4=Block |first4=G |last5=Wyrobek |first5=AJ |title=The association of folate, zinc and antioxidant intake with sperm aneuploidy in healthy non-smoking men |volume=23 |issue=5 |pages= 1–9 |year=2008 |pmid=18353905 |doi=10.1093/humrep/den036 | laysummary =http://www.medpagetoday.com/PrimaryCare/DietNutrition/tb/8825}}</ref> A benefit is indicated even for more than 700&nbsp;µg folate per day, which, though below the [[tolerable upper intake levels]] of 1,000&nbsp;µg/day, was 1.8 times the recommended dietary allowance.<ref name=Youngetal/> Folate is necessary for [[fertility]] in both men and women.  It contributes to [[spermatogenesis]].  Therefore, it is necessary  to receive sufficient amounts through the diet to avoid [[subfertility]].<ref name="Ebisch IM, Thomas CM, Peters WH, Braat DD, Steegers-Theunissen RP 2007 163–74"/>  Also, polymorphisms in genes of enzymes involved in folate metabolism could be one reason for fertility complications in some women with [[unexplained infertility]].<ref>{{cite doi|10.1016/j.fertnstert.2009.02.025}}</ref>

===Heart disease===
Taking folic acid does not reduce cardiovascular disease even though it reduces [[homocysteine]] levels.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bazzano|first=LA|title=No effect of folic acid supplementation on cardiovascular events, cancer or mortality after 5 years in people at increased cardiovascular risk, although homocysteine levels are reduced|journal=Evidence-based medicine|date=2011 Aug|volume=16|issue=4|pages=117–8|pmid=21402567|doi=10.1136/ebm1204}}</ref>

Folic acid supplements consumed before and during pregnancy may reduce the risk of heart defects in infants,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bazzano |first1 = LA | title = Folic acid supplementation and cardiovascular disease: the state of the art | journal = The American journal of the medical sciences | volume = 338 | issue = 1 | pages = 48–9 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19593104 | doi = 10.1097/MAJ.0b013e3181aaefd6 }}</ref>
and may reduce the risk for children to develop metabolic syndrome.<ref name="pmid19549749">{{cite journal | last1=Stewart | first1=CP |last2=Christian | first2=P | last3=Schulze | first3=KJ | last4=Leclerq | first4=SC | last5=West Jr | first5=KP | last6=Khatry | first6=SK |title=Antenatal micronutrient supplementation reduces metabolic syndrome in 6- to 8-year-old children in rural Nepal | journal=The Journal of nutrition | volume=139 | issue=8 | pages=1575–81 | year=2009 |pmid=19549749 | doi=10.3945/jn.109.106666 }}</ref>
That may, however, worsen the outcomes in people with cardiovascular disease such as angina and myocardial infarction.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Imasa| first1=MS | last2=Gomez | first2=NT | last3=Nevado Jr | first3=JB | title=Folic acid-based intervention in non-ST elevation acute coronary syndromes| journal=Asian cardiovascular & thoracic annals | volume=17 | issue=1 | pages=13–21 | year=2009 | pmid = 19515873 | doi=10.1177/0218492309102494}}</ref>

===Stroke===
Folic acid appears to reduce the risk of stroke, which may be due to the role folate plays in regulating homocysteine concentration. The reviews indicate the risk of stroke appears to be reduced only in some individuals, but a definite recommendation regarding supplementation beyond the current RDA has not been established for stroke prevention.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/6709101.stm |title=Folic acid 'reduces stroke risks' |date= 31 May 2007 | work=BBC News  | location = London}}</ref> Observed stroke reduction is consistent with the reduction in [[pulse pressure]] produced by folate supplementation of 5&nbsp;mg per day, since hypertension is a key risk factor for stroke. Folic supplements are inexpensive and relatively safe to use, which is why stroke or hyperhomocysteinemia patients are encouraged to consume daily B vitamins including folic acid.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Terwecoren | first1=A |last2=Steen | first2=E | last3=Benoit | first3=D | last4=Boon | first4=P | last5=Hemelsoet | first5=D | title=Ischemic stroke and hyperhomocysteinemia: truth or myth? | journal=Acta neurologica Belgica | volume=109 | issue=3 | pages=181–8 | year=2009 | pmid = 19902811 }}</ref>

===Cancer===
Many cancer cells have a high requirement for folic acid and overexpress the folic acid [[Cell surface receptor|receptor]].  This finding has led to the development of anti-cancer drugs that [[Folate targeting|target the folic acid receptor]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Leamon CP, Low PS |title=Delivery of macromolecules into living cells: a method that exploits folate receptor endocytosis |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. |volume=88 |issue=13 |pages=5572–6 |year=1991 |month=July |pmid=2062838 |pmc=51919 |doi=10.1073/pnas.88.13.5572}}</ref>

A [[meta-analysis]] published in 2010 failed to find a statistically significant cancer risk due to folic acid supplements.<ref>{{cite journal|journal= Archives of Internal Medicine  |year=2010|volume=170|issue=18|pages=1622–1631 |title=Effects of Lowering Homocysteine Levels With B Vitamins on Cardiovascular Disease, Cancer, and Cause-Specific Mortality Meta-analysis of 8 Randomized Trials Involving 37 485 Individuals|author=Clarke R et. al.|doi= 10.1001/archinternmed.2010.348|pmid= 20937919}}</ref>

Some investigations have proposed that good levels of folic acid may be related to lower risk of esophageal, stomach, and ovarian cancers, but the benefits of folic acid against cancer may depend on when it is taken and on individual conditions.  In addition, folic acid may not be helpful, and could even be damaging, in people already suffering from cancer or from a precancerous condition. Likewise, it has been suggested that excess folate may promote tumor initiation.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Am J Clin Nutr|date=1 November 2004|volume=80|issue=5|pages=1123–8 |title=Will mandatory folic acid fortification prevent or promote cancer?|author=Kim YI|pmid=15531657|url=http://www.ajcn.org/cgi/content/full/80/5/1123}}</ref> Folate has shown to play a dual role in cancer development; ''low'' folate intake protects against early carcinogenesis, and high folate intake promotes advanced carcinogenesis.<ref name="ReferenceC">{{cite journal | last1=Ulrich | first1=CM | title=Folate and cancer prevention: a closer look at a complex picture | journal=The American journal of clinical nutrition | volume=86 | issue=2 | pages=271–273 | year=2007 |pmid=17684194 }}</ref> Therefore, public health recommendations should be careful not to encourage too much folate intake.<ref name="ReferenceC"/>

Diets high in folate are associated with decreased risk of [[colorectal cancer]]; some studies show the association is stronger for folate from foods alone than for folate from foods and supplements,<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Int J Cancer |year=2005|volume=113|issue=5|pages=825–8 |title=Folate intake and colorectal cancer risk: a meta-analytical approach|author=Sanjoaquin MA, Allen N, Couto E, Roddam AW, Key TJ|doi=10.1002/ijc.20648|pmid=15499620}}</ref> Colorectal cancer is the most studied type of cancer in relation to folate and one carbon metabolism.  One study concluded that there was no strong support for an association between prostate cancer risk and circulating concentrations of folate or vitamin B12.  The researchers noted that while elevated concentrations of vitamin B12 may be associated with an increased risk for advanced stage prostate cancer, this was not true for folic acid and that the association between B12 and cancer risk required examination in other large prospective studies.<ref name="johansson2008">{{cite journal | last1 = Johansson | first1 = M | last2 = Appleby | first2 = PN | last3 = Allen | first3 = NE |last4 = Travis | first4 = RC | last5 = Roddam | first5 = AW | last6 = Egevad | first6 = L | last7 = Jenab | first7 = M | last8 = Rinaldi | first8 = S |last9 = Kiemeney | first9 = LA | title = Circulating concentrations of folate and vitamin B12 in relation to prostate cancer risk: results from the European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition study | journal = Cancer Epidemiology, Biomarkers & Prevention | volume = 17 | issue = 2| pages = 279–85 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18268110 | doi = 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-07-0657 }}</ref>

Most epidemiologic studies suggest diets high in folate are associated with decreased risk of [[breast cancer]], but results are not uniformly consistent. One broad cancer screening trial reported a potential harmful effect of much folate intake on breast cancer risk, suggesting routine folate supplementation should not be recommended as a breast cancer preventive,<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Nutr Rev |year=2006|volume=64|issue=10 Pt 1|pages=468–75 |title=Does a high folate intake increase the risk of breast cancer?|author=Kim YI|doi=10.1301/nr.2006.oct.468-475|pmid=17063929}}</ref> but a 2007 Swedish prospective study found  much folate intake was associated with a lower incidence of postmenopausal breast cancer.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Am J Clin Nutr |year=2007|volume=86|issue=2|pages=434–43 |title=High folate intake is associated with lower breast cancer incidence in postmenopausal women in the Malmö Diet and Cancer cohort|author=Ericson U, Sonestedt E, Gullberg B, Olsson H, Wirfält E|pmid=17684216}}</ref> A 2008 study has also shown no significant effect of folic acid on overall risk of total invasive cancer or breast cancer among women.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Zhang SM, Cook NR, Albert CM, Gaziano JM, Buring JE, [[JoAnn E. Manson|Manson JE]] |title=Effect of Combined Folic Acid, Vitamin B6, and Vitamin B12 on Cancer Risk: Results from a Randomized Trial|journal=JAMA|volume=300|issue=17|pages=2012–21 |year=2008|month= November|pmid=18984888|doi=10.1001/jama.2008.555 |url=http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/short/300/17/2012|pmc=2593624}}</ref> Folate intake may not have any effect on the risk of breast cancer but may have an effect for women who consume at least 15 g/d of alcohol.<ref name="Zhang S 1999">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1001/jama.281.17.1632 | last1 = Zhang | first1 = S | last2 = Hunter | year = 1999 | first2 = DJ | last3 = Hankinson | first3 = SE |last4 = Giovannucci | first4 = EL | last5 = Rosner | first5 = BA | last6 = Colditz | first6 = GA | last7 = Speizer | first7 = FE | last8 = Willett |first8 = WC | title = A Prospective Study of Folate Intake and the Risk of Breast Cancer | url = | journal = JAMA | volume = 281 | issue = 17| pages = 1632–1637 | pmid = 10235158 }}</ref> Folate intake of more than 300&nbsp;µg/d may reduce the risk of breast cancer in women who consume alcohol.<ref name="Zhang S 1999"/>

Most research studies associate high dietary folate intake with a reduced risk of prostate cancer.<ref name="johansson2008" />
<!-- however, in men, folic acid supplementation appears to double the risk of prostate cancer  cite web|url=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/news/fullstory_81528.html|title=MedlinePlus: Folic Acid Supplements Raise Prostate Cancer Risk|work=|accessdate= -->
Recently, a [[clinical trial]] showed daily supplementation of 1&nbsp;mg of folic acid increased the risk of [[prostate cancer]], while [[dietary]] and [[blood plasma|plasma]] folate levels among [[vitamin]] nonusers actually decreased the risk of [[prostate cancer]].<ref name="Figueiredo2009" />  A Finnish study consisting of 29,133 older male smokers observed prostate cancer risk had no relationship with serum folate levels.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

A 2013 study suggested that folate intake might be beneficial in the prevention of alcohol-associated [[hepatocellular carcinoma]].
<ref name="PerssonEC2013Alcohol">{{cite journal|last=Persson|first=EC|coauthors=Schwartz, LM; Park, Y; Trabert, B; Hollenbeck, AR; Graubard, BI; Freedman, ND; McGlynn, KA|title=Alcohol consumption, folate intake, hepatocellular carcinoma incidence and liver disease mortality|journal=Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev|date=10 January 2013|pmid=23307533}}</ref>{{Primary source-inline|date=January 2013}}

===Antifolates===
Folate is important for cells and tissues that rapidly divide.<ref name="Oldref_2"/> Cancer cells divide rapidly, and drugs that interfere with folate metabolism are used to treat cancer. The [[antifolate]] [[methotrexate]] is a drug often used to treat cancer because it inhibits the production of the active form of THF from the inactive dihydrofolate (DHF). However, methotrexate can be toxic,<ref name="Oldref_46">{{cite journal | author=Rubio IT, Cao Y, Hutchins LF, Westbrook KC, Klimberg VS | title=Effect of glutamine on methotrexate efficacy and toxicity | journal=Annals of Surgery |volume=227 | issue=5 | year=1998 | pages=772–8 | pmid=9605669 | doi = 10.1097/00000658-199805000-00018 | pmc=1191365}}</ref><ref name="Oldref_47">{{cite journal | author=Wolff JE, Hauch H, Kuhl J, Egeler RM, Jurgens H | title=Dexamethasone increases hepatotoxicity of MTX in children with brain tumors | journal=Anticancer Research | volume=18 | issue=4B | year=1998 | pages=2895–9 | pmid=9713483}}</ref><ref name="Oldref_48">{{cite journal | author=Kepka L, De Lassence A, Ribrag V, Gachot B, Blot F, Theodore C, Bonnay M, Korenbaum C, Nitenberg G |title=Successful rescue in a patient with high dose methotrexate-induced nephrotoxicity and acute renal failure | journal=Leukemia & Lymphoma |volume=29 | issue=1–2 | year=1998 | pages=205–9 | pmid=9638991 | doi = 10.3109/10428199809058397}}</ref>
producing side effects, such as inflammation in the digestive tract that make it difficult to eat normally. Also, bone marrow depression (inducing leukopenia and thrombocytopenia), and acute renal and hepatic failure have been reported.

[[Folinic acid]], under the drug name [[leucovorin]], a form of folate (formyl-THF), can help "rescue" or reverse the toxic effects of methotrexate.<ref name="Oldref_49">{{cite journal | author=Branda RF, Nigels E, Lafayette AR, Hacker M. | title=Nutritional folate status influences the efficacy and toxicity of chemotherapy in rats | journal=Blood | volume=92 | issue=7 | year=1998 | pages=2471–6 | pmid=9746787}}</ref>
Folinic acid is ''not'' the same as folic acid. Folic acid supplements have little established role in cancer chemotherapy.<ref name="Oldref_50">{{cite journal | author=Shiroky JB | title=The use of folates concomitantly with low-dose pulse methotrexate | journal=Rheumatic Diseases Clinics of North America | volume=23 | issue=4 | year=1997 | pages=969–80 | pmid=9361164 | doi=10.1016/S0889-857X(05)70369-0 | last2=Frcp(c)}}</ref><ref name="Oldref_51">{{cite journal| doi=10.1016/S0027-5107(97)00216-9 | author=Keshava C, Keshava N, Whong WZ, Nath J, Ong TM | title=Inhibition of methotrexate-induced chromosomal damage by folinic acid in V79 cells | journal=Mutation Research | volume=397 | issue=2 | year=1998 | pages=221–8 | pmid=9541646}}</ref>
There have been cases of severe adverse effects of accidental substitution of folic acid for folinic acid in patients receiving methotrexate cancer chemotherapy. It is important for anyone receiving methotrexate to follow medical advice on the use of folic or folinic acid supplements. The supplement of folinic acid in patients undergoing methotrexate treatment is to give cells dividing less rapidly enough folate to maintain normal cell functions. The amount of folate given will be depleted by rapidly dividing cells (cancer) very fast and so will not negate the effects of methotrexate.

===Psychological===
Some evidence links a shortage of folate with [[Clinical depression|depression]].<ref name="dep_coppen">{{cite journal | author=Coppen A, Bolander-Gouaille C.  | title= Treatment of depression: time to consider folic acid and vitamin B12 | journal= Journal of Psychopharmacology |volume=19 | issue=1 | year=2005 | pages=59–65  | pmid=15671130 | doi = 10.1177/0269881105048899}}</ref>
Limited evidence from [[Randomized controlled trials|randomised controlled trials]] showed using folic acid in addition to [[antidepressant]]s, to be specific [[selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor|SSRIs]], may have benefits.<ref name="dep_taylor">{{cite journal | author=Taylor MJ, Carney SM, Goodwin GM, Geddes JR. | title= Folate for depressive disorders: systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials | journal= Journal of Psychopharmacology | volume=18 | issue=2 | year=2004 | pages=251–6 | pmid=15260915 | doi = 10.1177/0269881104042630}}</ref> Research at the University of York and Hull York Medical School has found a link between depression and low levels of folate.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gilbody S, Lewis S, Lightfoot T  |title= Methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase (MTHFR) genetic polymorphisms and psychiatric disorders: a HuGE review|journal=American Journal of Epidemiology |volume=165 |issue=1 |pages=1–13  |year=2007 |month=January |pmid=17074966 |doi= 10.1093/aje/kwj347|url=http://aje.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/165/1/1}}</ref>  One study by the same team involved 15,315 subjects.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gilbody S, Lightfoot T, Sheldon T  |title=Is low folate a risk factor for depression? A meta‐analysis and exploration of heterogeneity|journal=Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health |volume=61 |issue=7 |pages=631–637  |year=2007 |month=July |pmid=17568057 |doi= 10.1136/jech.2006.050385|url= |pmc=2465760}}</ref>  However, the evidence is probably too limited at present for this to be a routine treatment recommendation.
Folic acid supplementation affects [[noradrenaline]] and [[serotonin]] receptors within the brain, which could be the cause of folic acid's possible ability to act as an antidepressant.<ref name="Gaweesh S p 29">Gaweesh S, Ewies AA. Med Hypotheses. 2009 Sep 29. Folic acid supplementation cures hot flushes in postmenopausal women.</ref>

<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = García-Miss Mdel|first1 = R |last2 = Pérez-Mutul |first2 = J |last3 = López-Canul |first3 = B |last4 = Solís-Rodríguez |first4 = F |last5 = Puga-Machado |first5 = L|last6 = Oxté-Cabrera |first6 = A |last7 = Gurubel-Maldonado |first7 = J |last8 = Arankowsky-Sandoval |first8 = G |title = Folate, homocysteine, interleukin-6, and tumor necrosis factor alfa levels, but not the methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase C677T polymorphism, are risk factors for schizophrenia |journal = Journal of Psychiatric Research |volume = 44 |issue = 7 |pages = 441–6 |year = 2010 |pmid = 19939410 |doi = 10.1016/j.jpsychires.2009.10.011 }}</ref> The exact mechanisms involved in the development of schizophrenia are not entirely clear, but may have something to do with [[DNA methylation]] and one carbon metabolism, and these are the precise roles of folate in the body.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Krebs | first1 = MO | last2 = Bellon | first2 = A | last3 = Mainguy | first3 = G | last4 = Jay | first4 = TM | last5 = Frieling | first5 = H | title = One-carbon metabolism and schizophrenia: current challenges and future directions | journal = Trends in molecular medicine | volume = 15 | issue = 12| pages = 562–70 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19896901 | doi = 10.1016/j.molmed.2009.10.001 }}</ref>

===Macular degeneration===
A substudy of the Women's Antioxidant and Folic Acid Cardiovascular Study published in 2009 reported use of a nutritional supplement containing folic acid, [[pyridoxine]], and [[cyanocobalamin]] decreased the risk of developing [[age-related macular degeneration]] by 34.7%.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Christen WG, Glynn RJ, Chew EY, Albert CM, [[JoAnn E. Manson|Manson JE]]  |title=Folic Acid, Vitamin B6, and Vitamin B12 in Combination and Age-related Macular Degeneration in a Randomized Trial of Women |journal=Arch Intern Med|volume=169 |issue=4 |pages=335–41  |year=2009 |pmid= 19237716  |doi=10.1001/archinternmed.2008.574 |pmc=2648137 }}</ref>

===Folic Acid, B<sub>12</sub> and Iron===
There is a complex interaction between folic acid, [[Vitamin B12|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]] and iron. A deficiency of one may be "masked" by excess of another so the three must be in balance.<ref>{{cite web|author=G Vreugdenhil, A W Wognum, H G van Eijk, A J Swaak |url=http://ard.bmj.com/content/49/2/93.short |title=Anaemia in rheumatoid arthritis: the role of iron, vitamin B12, and folic acid deficiency, and erythropoietin responsiveness. - Vreugdenhil et al. 49 (2): 93 - Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases |publisher=Ard.bmj.com |date=1990-02-01 |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1474442206705981 |title=Elsevier: Article Locator |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/ajh.2830340204/abstract |title=Diagnosis of cobalamin deficiency I: Usefulness of serum methylmalonic acid and total homocysteine concentrations - Allen - 2006 - American Journal of Hematology - Wiley Online Library |publisher=Onlinelibrary.wiley.com |date=2006-07-11 |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref>

===Toxicity===

The risk of toxicity from folic acid is low, because folate is a water-soluble vitamin and is regularly removed from the body through urine.<ref name="Oldref_55">{{cite journal | author=Hathcock JN. | title=Vitamins and minerals: efficacy and safety | journal=American Journal of Clinical Nutrition | volume=66 | issue=2 | year=1997 | pages=427–37 | pmid=9250127}}</ref> One potential issue associated with high dosages of folic acid is that it has a [[masking effect]] on the diagnosis of [[pernicious anaemia]] (vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency),<ref name="FAOWHO2002"/> and a variety of concerns{{clarify|date=October 2012}} of potential negative impacts on health.<ref name="adavidsmith" />

===Folate deficiency===
{{main|Folate deficiency}}
[[Folate deficiency]] may lead to [[glossitis]], diarrhea, depression, confusion, anemia, and fetal [[neural tube defect]]s and brain defects (during pregnancy).<ref name="merck.com">http://www.merck.com</ref> Folate deficiency is accelerated by alcohol consumption.<ref name="Diaz, V. H 2008">Diaz, V. H. US Patent 20080020071, Jan 24, 2008.</ref> Folate deficiency is diagnosed by analyzing [[Complete blood count|CBC]] and plasma vitamin B<sub>12</sub> and folate levels.<ref name="merck.com"/> CBC may indicate megaloblastic anemia but this could also be a sign of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency.<ref name="merck.com"/> A serum folate of 3 μg/L or lower indicates deficiency.<ref name="merck.com"/> Serum folate level reflects folate status but erythrocyte folate level better reflects tissue stores after intake.<ref name="merck.com"/> An erythrocyte folate level of 140 μg/L or lower indicates inadequate folate status.<ref name="merck.com"/> Increased homocysteine level suggests tissue folate deficiency but homocysteine is also affected by vitamin B<sub>12</sub> and vitamin B<sub>6</sub>, renal function, and genetics.<ref name="merck.com"/> One way to differentiate between folate deficiency from vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency is by testing for methylmalonic acid levels.<ref name="merck.com"/> Normal MMA levels indicate folate deficiency and elevated MMA levels indicate vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency.<ref name="merck.com"/> Folate deficiency is treated with supplemental oral folate of 400 to 1000 μg per day.<ref name="merck.com"/> This treatment is very successful in replenishing tissues, even if deficiency was caused by malabsorption.<ref name="merck.com"/> Patients with megaloblastic anemia need to be tested for vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency before folate treatment, because if the patient has vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency, folate supplementation can remove the anemia, but can also worsen neurologic problems.<ref name="merck.com"/> Morbidly obese patients with BMIs of greater than 50 are more likely to develop folate deficiency.<ref name="Malterre T 2009 247–57">{{cite journal |author=Malterre T  |title=Digestive and nutritional considerations in celiac disease: could supplementation help? |journal=Alternative Medicine Review |volume=14|issue=3 |pages=247–57  |year=2009 |month=September |pmid=19803549 |url=http://www.thorne.com/altmedrev/.fulltext/14/3/247.pdf}}{{Unreliable medical source|date=August 2010}}</ref>
Patients with celiac disease have a higher chance of developing folate deficiency.<ref name="Malterre T 2009 247–57"/>
Cobalamin deficiency may lead to folate deficiency, which, in turn, increases homocysteine levels and may result in the development of cardiovascular disease or birth defects.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Varela-Moreiras G, Murphy MM, Scott JM  |title=Cobalamin, folic acid, and homocysteine |journal=Nutrition Reviews |volume=67 |issue=Suppl 1 |pages=S69–72  |year=2009 |month=May |pmid=19453682|doi=10.1111/j.1753-4887.2009.00163.x}}</ref>

=== Malaria ===
Some studies show iron-folic acid supplementation in children under 5 may result in increased mortality due to [[malaria]]; this has prompted the World Health Organization to alter their iron-folic acid supplementation policies for children in malaria-prone areas, such as India.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pasricha S, Shet A, Sachdev HP, Shet AS  |title=Risks of routine iron and folic acid supplementation for young children |journal=Indian Pediatrics |volume=46 |issue=10 |pages=857–66  |year=2009 |month=October |pmid=19887691 |url=http://www.indianpediatrics.net/oct2009/857.pdf}}</ref>

=== Aging ===
A study published in 2010 showed that folic acid has an effect on [[antiglycation]] in ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'', which affords the cultures protection against higher sugar levels that normally lead to the death of the culture. The same study also showed that too much folic acid is toxic to cells. Because of this, the authors theorized that folic acid could potentially have an effect on aging since glycation tends to increase with age.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pepper ED, Farrell MJ, Nord G, Finkel SE  |title=Antiglycation Effects of Carnosine and Other Compounds on the Long-Term Survival of Escherichia coli |journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology |volume=76 |issue=24 |pages=7925–30  |year=2010 |month=December |pmid=20952637 |url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20952637}}</ref>

== Dietary reference intake ==
Because of the difference in bioavailability between supplemented folic acid and the different forms of folate found in food, the dietary folate equivalent (DFE) system was established. One DFE is defined as 1 μg (microgram) of dietary folate, or 0.6 μg of folic acid supplement.

