The [[Dietary Reference Intake]] (DRIs) were developed by the [[United States National Academy of Sciences]] to set reference values for planning and assessing nutrient intake for healthy people.  DRIs incorporate two reference values, the [[Reference Daily Intake]] (RDI, the daily intake level that is adequate for 97–98% of the population in the United States where the standards were set) and [[tolerable upper intake levels]] (UL, the highest level of intake that is known to avoid toxicity).  The UL for folate refers to only synthetic folate, as no health risks have been associated with high intake of folate from food sources.<ref name="NIH-Gov"/>

